    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Aim</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">This paper presents the initial results of a project devoted to creating the first-ever FAIR model for handwritten text recognition (HTR) of Old Norse-Icelandic manuscripts, accompanied by an open-access dataset of ground truths for manuscripts from the 13
                    <hi rend="superscript">th</hi> and 14
                    <hi rend="superscript">th</hi> centuries–the golden age of manuscript production in Iceland. Compared with other medieval languages written in Latin scripts, Old Norse-Icelandic does not benefit from the same amount of training data, which are crucial for developing strong HTR models. Therefore, we turn to an approach applied by scholars in other under-resourced fields, such as Arabic, to find sustainable solutions for the acquisition of texts. The goal of this paper is not only the presentation of another HTR model and its underlying dataset.<ref n="1" target="ftn1"/> By incrementally evaluating the accuracy of the model, we provide insights into the amount of data actually needed to produce usable transcriptions. We provide reflections on the accessibility and influence of technology on research in smaller, often under-resourced disciplines, as well as on the position of individual researchers who are based outside large DH centres benefiting from state-of-the-art infrastructure. We also position our experiments with HTR in the broader context of research questions concerning Icelandic palaeography and scribal culture. One of the important points demonstrated by our paper is that all training and testing were done with Kraken 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"6lOU0Hte","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Kiessling 2019)","plainCitation":"(Kiessling 2019)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2014,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/M5Y5479G"],"itemData":{"id":2014,"type":"paper-conference","container-title":"Digital Humanities Book of Abstracts","DOI":"https://dev.clariah.nl/files/dh2019/boa/0673.html","event-place":"Utrecht","event-title":"Annual ADHO conference","publisher-place":"Utrecht","title":"Kraken – A Universal Text Recognizer for the Humanities","author":[{"family":"Kiessling","given":"B"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2019"]]},"citation-key":"kiessling2019a"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Kiessling 2019), run locally on a 2020 M1 MacBook Air (8 CPU, 16 GB). A comparable machine today can be purchased for around EUR 1.000, making it more accessible for many researchers than obtaining access to GPUs. 
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Background</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">While medieval Iceland is by many exclusively associated with vikings, volcanoes, and glaciers, few know that it was also home to impressive cultural production including the composition of native literature and the production of countless manuscripts. The Old Norse-Icelandic literary corpus has hitherto received little attention from the HTR community. While there are over 900 Icelandic manuscripts produced between the twelfth and the sixteenth centuries, only a fraction of them has been used in scholarly editions and even fewer in digital ones. A significant portion of these manuscripts (at least 50%), however, has already been digitised, and thousands of high-quality digital images are freely available online. Hence, there is great and hitherto unexploited potential for leveraging computer-assisted methods to approach this material and make it more accessible to the scholarly community by producing auto-generated transcriptions. The applications for auto-generated transcriptions are countless and already play an important role in digital palaeographical and philological workflows in certain fields of medieval studies, e.g. Latin, German, and French, but are much less common in smaller fields. Captivated by the great promise of generic HTR models that they can be easily and quickly fine-tuned for new contexts without great computational effort, we decided to test the applicability of existing HTR models for the Icelandic context and the amount of data needed to fine-tune them. </p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Dataset and Method</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Starting with the Icelandic TranscriboQuest2024 dataset 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"hQUNXgyg","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Kapitan et al. 2024)","plainCitation":"(Kapitan et al. 2024)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2017,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/YXK9Z36J"],"itemData":{"id":2017,"type":"dataset","DOI":"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13757377","title":"TranscriboQuest24 Icelandic [dataset]","author":[{"family":"Kapitan","given":"KA"},{"family":"Latham","given":"K"},{"family":"Pinche","given":"A"},{"family":"Verri","given":"G"},{"family":"Yavuz","given":"NK"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024"]]},"citation-key":"kapitan2024"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Kapitan et al. 2024), we used eScriptorium for additional data acquisition 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"Kf3daNzZ","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Stokes et al. 2021; Kiessling et al. 2019)","plainCitation":"(Stokes et al. 2021; Kiessling et al. 2019)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2015,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/8WALASEA"],"itemData":{"id":2015,"type":"chapter","container-title":"Classics@18: Ancient Manuscripts and Virtual Research Environments","title":"The eScriptorium VRE for Manuscript Cultures","URL":"https://classics-at.chs.harvard.edu/classics18-stokes-kiessling-stokl-ben-ezra-tissot-gargem/","author":[{"family":"Stokes","given":"P"},{"family":"Kiessling","given":"B"},{"family":"Stökl Ben Ezra","given":"D"},{"family":"Tissot","given":"R"},{"family":"Gargem","given":"H"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2021"]]},"citation-key":"stokes2021"}},{"id":2016,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/34FLE8TP"],"itemData":{"id":2016,"type":"paper-conference","container-title":"2019 International Conference on Document Analysis and Recognition Workshops (ICDARW)","DOI":"http://doi.org/10.1109/ICDARW.2019.10032","title":"eScriptorium: An Open Source Platform for Historical Document Analysis","author":[{"family":"Kiessling","given":"B"},{"family":"Tissot","given":"R"},{"family":"Stökl Ben Ezra","given":"D"},{"family":"Stokes","given":"P"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2019"]]},"citation-key":"kiessling2019"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Stokes et al. 2021; Kiessling et al. 2019), creating the corpus summarised in Table 1. The transcriptions of all manuscripts, with the exception of AM 334 fol., the transcription of which is based on the digital facsimiles prepared with the aid of the printed edition 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"gz9lxKB2","properties":{"formattedCitation":"({\\i{}Gr\\uc0\\u225{}g\\uc0\\u225{}s Efter Det Arnamagn\\uc0\\u230{}anske Haandskrift Nr. 334 Fol., Sta\\uc0\\u240{}arh\\uc0\\u243{}lsb\\uc0\\u243{}k} 1879)","plainCitation":"(Grágás Efter Det Arnamagnæanske Haandskrift Nr. 334 Fol., Staðarhólsbók 1879)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2023,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/SX9URFF3"],"itemData":{"id":2023,"type":"book","event-place":"Copenhagen","publisher-place":"Copenhagen","title":"Grágás efter det Arnamagnæanske Haandskrift Nr. 334 fol., Staðarhólsbók","issued":{"date-parts":[["1879"]]},"citation-key":"1879"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(
                    <hi rend="italic">Grágás</hi> 1879), are based on the MENOTA corpus 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"Iy9HMlYR","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Odd Einar Haugen et al. 2019)","plainCitation":"(Odd Einar Haugen et al. 2019)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2021,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/RL9TJMPQ"],"itemData":{"id":2021,"type":"standard","title":"Handbook 3.0: Guidelines for the electronic encoding of Medieval Nordic primary sources","URL":"https://www.menota.org/HB3_index.xml","author":[{"literal":"Odd Einar Haugen"},{"literal":"Ivar Berg"},{"literal":"Marco Bianchi"},{"literal":"Haraldur Bernharðsson"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2019"]]},"citation-key":"oddeinarhaugen2019"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Haugen et al. 2019). The layout for most of the manuscripts was corrected by Ariane Pinche in eScriptorium, and the others were done by Chahan Vidal-Gorène in Calfa Vision 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"yhbHLd9l","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Vidal-Gor\\uc0\\u232{}ne et al. 2021)","plainCitation":"(Vidal-Gorène et al. 2021)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2022,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/EZD5UX4R"],"itemData":{"id":2022,"type":"paper-conference","container-title":"Document Analysis and Recognition – ICDAR","DOI":"hal-03971691","title":"A Modular and Automated Annotation Platform for Handwritings: Evaluation on Under-Resourced Languages","author":[{"family":"Vidal-Gorène","given":"C"},{"family":"Dupin","given":"Boris"},{"family":"Decours-Perez","given":"Aliénor"},{"family":"Riccioli","given":"Thomas"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2021"]]},"citation-key":"vidal-gorene2021"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Vidal-Gorène et al. 2021). 
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">For the model, we took our point of departure in the recent efforts to create a generic model for Latin medieval manuscripts. We used the recently released CATMuS-medieval model 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"kXEjKiah","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Pinche 2023; Cl\\uc0\\u233{}rice et al. 2024; Pinche et al. 2024)","plainCitation":"(Pinche 2023; Clérice et al. 2024; Pinche et al. 2024)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2018,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/NBT6KJT2"],"itemData":{"id":2018,"type":"article-journal","container-title":"Journal of Data Mining and Digital Humanities","DOI":"hal-03837519v4","title":"Generic HTR Models for Medieval Manuscripts. The CREMMALab Project","author":[{"family":"Pinche","given":"Ariane"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2023"]]},"citation-key":"pinche2023"}},{"id":2019,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/5RIAG7II"],"itemData":{"id":2019,"type":"paper-conference","DOI":"hal-04453952","event-title":"International Conference on Document Analysis and Recognition (ICDAR)","title":"CATMuS Medieval: A multilingual large-scale cross-century dataset in Latin script for handwritten text recognition and beyond","author":[{"family":"Clérice","given":"Thibault"},{"family":"Pinche","given":"Ariane"},{"family":"Vlachou-Efstathiou","given":"Malamatenia"},{"family":"Chagué","given":"Alix"},{"family":"Camps","given":"Jean-Baptiste"},{"family":"Gille-Levenson","given":"Matthias"},{"family":"Brisville-Fertin","given":"Olivier"},{"family":"Fischer","given":"Franz"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024"]]},"citation-key":"clerice2024"},"label":"page"},{"id":2020,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/UWGYUSUL"],"itemData":{"id":2020,"type":"dataset","DOI":"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.12743230","title":"CATMuS Medieval (1.5.0)","author":[{"family":"Pinche","given":"Ariane"},{"family":"Clérice","given":"Thibault"},{"family":"Chagué","given":"A"},{"family":"Camps","given":"J-B"},{"family":"Vlachou-Efstathiou","given":"M"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024"]]},"citation-key":"pinche2024"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Pinche 2023; Clérice et al. 2024; Pinche et al. 2024). Following the example of Lucas 
                    <hi rend="italic">et al.</hi>
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"XZ30YilG","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(2022)","plainCitation":"(2022)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2013,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/6T5A98NZ"],"itemData":{"id":2013,"type":"article-journal","DOI":"hal-03874725","title":"New Results for the Text Recognition of Arabic Maghribī Manuscripts - Managing an Under-resourced Script (pre-print)","author":[{"family":"Lucas","given":"N"},{"family":"Salah","given":"C"},{"family":"Vidal-Gorène","given":"C"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2022"]]},"citation-key":"lucas2022"},"label":"page","suppress-author":true}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(2022), we fine-tuned it incrementally using two manuscripts as training data. We tested its performance on four manuscripts, two in-domain manuscripts (but with different page ranges) and two out-of-domain manuscripts.
                </p>
