            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Results and Discussion</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The fine-tuning process of the CATMuS-medieval model demonstrates significant improvement in both character and word accuracy across in-domain and out-of-domain datasets. As presented in Table 2 and Figure 5, just eight pages of training data improved the model’s performance by 20 percent points. Initially, at Step 0 (without fine-tuning), CATMuS-medieval exhibited character accuracy around 65.8% and word accuracy below 20%, with frequent errors in spacing, punctuation, similar letters (‘i’ vs. ‘u’), and combining marks. Step 1 (two images in training) brought substantial gains, especially in-domain, with character accuracy rising to 83.1% and word accuracy surpassing 50%, while errors in spacing and punctuation decreased noticeably. Out-of-domain performance improved more slowly but steadily. By Step 2 (two more images), error rates for combining marks and rare characters decreased, with character accuracy reaching 85.2% in-domain and 72.8% out-of-domain. Word accuracy continued to rise, reaching 54.7% in-domain. Persistent issues included confusion between similar letters and combining marks. Step 3 marked further reduction in frequent errors, such as mistaking ‘m’ for ‘n’, with character accuracy climbing to 86.2% in-domain and 73.2% out-of-domain. Finally, Step 4 achieved the best results, with in-domain character accuracy at 88.0% and word accuracy at 63.0%. Out-of-domain improvements were slower but consistent. </p>
