                <p style="text-align: left; text-align: center;">
                    <hi rend="bold" style="font-size:10pt">Figure 6.</hi>
                    <hi style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve"> Heatmaps illustrating the evolution of the most frequent error types made by the model across steps, both in-domain and out-of-domain. Each row represents a specific confusion type with colour intensity indicating error rate (top) and error count (bottom). Brighter colours denote higher error frequencies.</hi>
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Overall, as illustrated by the heatmaps in Figure 6, fine-tuning with incremental data led to effective error reduction in both in-domain and out-of-domain settings, with in-domain data benefiting more significantly. The improvement in the “Letter → Letter” error category (replacing one standard alphanumeric character with another) is the most pronounced, with absolute error counts decreasing across stages. Simultaneously, error rates also decrease substantially for punctuation, especially in the “Punctuation → Punctuation” and “Punctuation → Special” categories. Improvements across other categories, particularly those involving diacritics are less clear, suggesting that fine-tuning with a small amount of data primarily benefits standard character recognition rather than more complex or less frequent tokens.</p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Finally, as visually oriented humanists, we turned back to eScriptorium for a more visual representation of the performance. We managed to get some good lines, which were almost completely correct (Figure 7), but also some awful lines (Figure 8). </p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1007" width="13.629675cm" height="5.241372222222222cm" url="/tmp/tmpctcydl59/Pictures/d8464f79d68062a6160f98a40815a508.png" rend="inline"/>
                </figure>
                <p style="text-align: left; text-align: center;">
                    <hi rend="bold" style="font-size:10pt">Figure 7.</hi>
                    <hi style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve"> A success story: AM 519 a 4to, 2v:23. A screenshot showing the comparison of the manual transcription with the text predictions by CATMuS and our model in eScriptorium.</hi>
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1008" width="13.713258333333334cm" height="6.311194444444444cm" url="/tmp/tmpctcydl59/Pictures/d8464f79d68062a6160f98a40815a508.png" rend="inline"/>
                </figure>
                <p style="text-align: left; text-align: center;">
                    <hi rend="bold" style="font-size:10pt">Figure 8.</hi>
                    <hi style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve"> Not-so-much of a success story, AM 519 a 4to, 2v:7. A screenshot showing the comparison of the manual transcription with the text predictions by CATMuS and our model in eScriptorium.</hi>
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The types of errors observed allow us to revise the transcription guidelines for the next iteration of our experiments. Originally, prioritising the characteristics of Old Norse-Icelandic manuscripts, we decided to add multiple special characters to the CATMuS character set. Among them were those representing the phonetic system of Old Norse-Icelandic, such as the vowels introduced by the First Grammatical Treatise ‘ǫ’, ‘ę’, ‘ø’, and the fricatives ‘þ’ and ‘ð’ 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"yDQXfu66","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Gu\\uc0\\u240{}var\\uc0\\u240{}ur M\\uc0\\u225{}r Gunnlaugsson 2008; Stef\\uc0\\u225{}n Karlsson 2002)","plainCitation":"(Guðvarður Már Gunnlaugsson 2008; Stefán Karlsson 2002)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":330,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/MQSP6395"],"itemData":{"id":330,"type":"chapter","collection-number":"5","collection-title":"Veröffentlichungen der Kommission für Schrift- und Buchwesen des Mittelalters","container-title":"Régionalisme et Internationalisme – Problémes de Paléographie et de Codicologie du Moyen Age. Actes du XVe Colloque du Comité International de Paléographie Latine (13-17 September 2005)","event-place":"Wien","language":"eng","note":"bibtex: gudvardurmargunnlaugsson2008","page":"87-97","publisher":"Verlag der Österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften","publisher-place":"Wien","title":"The origin and development of Icelandic script","author":[{"literal":"Guðvarður Már Gunnlaugsson"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2008"]]},"citation-key":"gudvardurmargunnlaugsson2008"}},{"id":1542,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/2826034/items/FZ2L8WUS"],"itemData":{"id":1542,"type":"chapter","container-title":"The Nordic Languages: An International Handbook of the History of the North Germanic Languages","event-place":"Berlin","page":"832-840","publisher":"De Gruyter","publisher-place":"Berlin","title":"The development of Latin script II: in Iceland","volume":"1","author":[{"literal":"Stefán Karlsson"}],"editor":[{"family":"Bandle","given":"Oskar"},{"family":"Braunmüller","given":"Kurt"},{"family":"Jahr","given":"Ernst Håkon"},{"family":"Karker","given":""},{"family":"Naumann","given":"Hans-Peter"},{"family":"Teleman","given":"Ulf"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2002"]]},"citation-key":"stefankarlsson2002a"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Guðvarður Már Gunnlaugsson 2008; Stefán Karlsson 2002). We also included some characters which appear in continental manuscripts but are ignored in CATMuS. For example, ‘r-rotunda’, which does not occur in the earliest Icelandic manuscripts but becomes increasingly common from the 13
                    <hi rend="superscript">th</hi> century onwards. Depending on which letters it follows, it gives us clues about chronology and may serve as evidence for the u-insertion, which appears around 1300 and becomes common by the late 14
                    <hi rend="superscript">th</hi> century. At the same time, to minimise the number of classes, we were not equally inclusive for all characters, e.g., ‘d’ and ‘uncial-d’, and this decision seems to confuse the model. When the manuscript features an ‘uncial-d’ for {d}, our model transcribes it as ‘ð’ (see Figure 8). This prompts further consideration of whether such characters should be reintroduced into the training data. 
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Therefore, these experiments allowed us to refine the principles and objectives for a larger-scale project whose primary goal is to expand the training dataset by producing transcriptions of new manuscripts. This will allow us to train new models in different configurations, test their performance, and assess the impact of an increased number of classes. Furthermore, it will facilitate discussions about the trade-offs between data modelling and the ability to address specific palaeographic questions regarding the chronological distribution of ‘r-rotunda’, ‘insular-f’, ‘uncial-d’, and the various shapes of the Tironian nota.</p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">At the current stage of the project, our study demonstrates that even four pages per manuscript are sufficient for fine-tuning the CATMuS-medieval model, significantly improving its performance. Our results are promising, showcasing that HTR technology can be successfully used in Old Norse-Icelandic studies. Moreover, our case demonstrates that fine-tuning existing models with Kraken can be done easily and locally on an affordable machine, without requiring GPU access, or a subscription to external infrastructure, thus highlighting the accessibility of HTR technology today. We are finally able to offer a quick, open-access solution for scholars interested in incorporating HTR models into their research workflows, even if they are not directly involved in HTR development.</p>
